metadata.name: M'Fing Dots on a M'Fing Grid #15
metadata.description:
M'Fing Dots on a M'Fing Grid was an fxhash speedrun any% < 720 minutes project. Started at 10:30am Fri 5th August 2022, and finished at 10:30pm Fri 5th August 2022.

The repo for the code base can be found at: https://github.com/revdancatt/mfing-dots-on-a-mfing-grid - progress of writing code over the 12 hours can be seen in the commit history.

## THE PROJECT

The idea behind the project was to take one of the simplest things in generative art, randomly coloured dots on a grid.

Many projects use dots on a grid as the base foundation for building more complexity. However, just the dots themselves are often considered too simple to have as a project on their own.

Given the limited amount of time for a 12-hour speed run, I decided to see if I could take something as simple as dots and inject just a little bit of GenArt personality into it. Adding textures, variations and controlled colour selection.

It's about as simple you can get with dots on a grid, without being simple. This is my [speed run] version, show me yours.

## SPEED RUN

The tradition of doing a "speed run" on fxhash was started by Alexis AndrÃ© (@MacTuitui) and his "fxhash SpeedRun: any% < 960 minutes" project (#11995), described as "A performance piece. From cloning the template to a decent piece in less than 960 minutes".

Two more speed run collections have been created "Consequence Broadcast" (#13359) and "Beacon" (#17542) both by Amy Goodchild.

This is a fxhash speedrun any% < 720 run.

The any% is from game speed running and means "to get to the end with any % finished", meaning you don't have to 100% complete the game, just get to the end credits. For a gen art project it means you can use libraries and copy bits and bobs from your previous code, without having to do everything from scratch.

< 720 means that it's done in less than 720 minutes, in this case 12 hours.

metadata.name: Sparsely Populated Grid #91
metadata.description:
â€œSparsely Populated Gridâ€ is the result of an architectâ€™s fascination with Cartographies and a crypto-enthusiast love for Neo Punk aesthetics. The first sketch, drawn by hand with Procreate, was made in October 2021.

This is an exploration on the field of Generative Cartographies, an abstract diagrammatic representation of a randomly generated area within the virtual IPFS world. Everything starts with an GRID of varying sizes and angles, subsequently POPULATED by a random number of forms. But, how to populate the grid? SPARSELY, of course, with just the right amount of superpositions.

The algorithm produces varying compositions of fourteen different forms, with seven possible mixes and ten colour palettes. Movement, made possible by its generative digital nature, follows sinusoidal patterns, as if the forms breathed and danced to an unheard music.

Besides, they never forget to celebrate birthdays.


// INTERACTIVITY

- CLICK or SPACEBAR to stop movement.
- UP and DOWN ARROWS to Disable/Enable graphic elements such as texts (wink).
- LEFT and RIGHT ARROWS (when stopped) to Move frames back and forth.
- Press 1 for a low-res PNG.
- Press 2 for a medium-res PNG (3x).
- Press 3 for a hi-res PNG (6x).
- Press G for Glitch (low-res).
- Press P for PixelArt (low-res).

If you want a different resolution, you can also add ?&res=xxx to the url to get your desired output. Then simply Right-Click SAVE the canvas -- experimental

metadata.name: COMPUTERS #60
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from pixel array computations and classic noise algorithms.

COMPUTERS is a meditation on the aesthetics of computing in all of its forms. It recalls the types of computation required to build temples, write complex texts, weave detailed textiles, and program computer games. Pixels have always existed in some form or another, before and after the screen. Every iteration of COMPUTERS suggests that computation is both contemporary and ancient.

Press 'p' or click to pause the animation.
Press 's' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: CHRONUS #14
metadata.description:
Following the use of simple shapes as the main element, combined with the alternation and overlapping of layers and blending modes, "CHRONUS" adds the temporal dimension as one of the elements that form what is seen.

Furthermore, the different gradations, associated with the play of lights and shadows, reveal the unusual as an image.

Nothing is just one thing.

#Main Features
- 13 color schemes â€œzonesâ€:

* Vascai, Shadow Sky and Bronze â€“ 12,5% chance
* Burnt Golden - 10% chance
* Lemonade - 8,5% chance
* Red Browned, Rec, Tif and Soldier - 7,5% chance
* Lushtemple and 80â€™s â€“ 5% chance
* BR - 2,5% chance
* B&W - 1,5% chance

- 3 canvas formats;
- 3 times of run;
- 3 patterns;
- 3 degrees of color saturation;

Obs.:
- The first 3 iterations will entitle you to 1 free edition of my next project on FxHash.
- The "STEEL" palette entitles you to 1 free edition of my next project on FxHash.
- The rendering process should take a few seconds, so enjoy the look of the circles in action.

september 14, 2022

Generative Token by Morbeck for fxhash.

metadata.name: Petri 1500 v2 QHD  #53
metadata.description:
Petri 1500 is a celebration of reaching 1500 Twitter followers.
As I've grown as an artist what represents that growth but a petri dish, filled with life, finding a way.

There is a bug in the original version that cause display issues on retina & QHD displays. So this version fixes that, is free to all that held a copy at 00:30 14-09-2022 and a few spares for luck.

A sillybration of all things fx(hash) featuring some of my recognisable pallets and primatives
along with something new to me - noise and 'realistic' nature sketches.
All mashed for pure fun.

L to download 1000x1000
S to download 4000x4000
H to download 8000x8000

metadata.name: Overlay #55
metadata.description:
Overlay is inspired by the double exposure of analog photography and the 4-Color Process screen printing technique, where images are superimposed, mixing their
colors to form new ones, shapes are also mixed, sometimes they look like mountains, sometimes waves.

The initial price at unlocking will be 12 xtz. every 5 minutes, it will be reduced by 3 xtz to the death price of 1 xtz.

metadata.name: KINJO! #272
metadata.description:
A celebration of my 1 year in the Tezos art space, KINJO is an experiment in pure abstraction and randomness. With a simple grid at its core, this piece attempts to play with lively colors, completely unique variations, and host the nice surprises that randomness can bring.

My intention when starting to work in the Tezos space was to play with the surrender of control in art, that idea had always fascinated me. In the beginning it was working with GAN, digitally painting a piece or processing my own photography, and sending it through my own frankensteined colab notebook. I was creating something and then trusting a process to rip it apart and create something new. I moved on to the Ganerations project, which was essentially gen art in layered pngs and processed through my GAN notebook. I found generative art and fxHash shortly after and have been incredibly thankful for the community here, as well as inspired every day by the new approaches I see from both new and established artists on the platform. I'm learning every day.

Gen art is the perfect place for me to express myself and explore the themes of control and trust with my work, and I thank you all for following along and supporting my work :)

metadata.name: Jajim #172
metadata.description:
The main idea of the "Jajim" is to divide a square into smaller parts in such a way that each variation has its original and unique composition. The role of lines is such that sometimes they help the dynamics of the composition and sometimes they appear in the form of texture and its contrast with empty spaces leads to the visual richness of the work. I avoided drawing various visual elements in favor of clarity of composition. Also, in order to avoid exaggeration, I used colors sparingly because I think they will have a stronger impact in their occasional presence.

Created using p5.js.

metadata.name: CONCENTRIX #8
metadata.description:
CONCENTRIX is my first shot to mimic a water color brush as generative art. Each edition has between 5 and 11 circles, and every frame results in a different concentric circle. For background opted to mimic a brushed steel. 

Hope you like it as much as I love programming it.

Made with love in p5js
by @codeNFT September, 2022
